items.content_text: Undescribed Edosa species. The darkish spot/line on the forewings is not an aberration but rather a mark consistent on both sides.

items.title: Ardozyga spp.
items.content_text: This has been identified by Ted Edwards (ANIC) as Ardozyga nr phloeodes.

items.title: (Dasygaster) epundoides
items.content_text: This is listed as Species Inquirenda in Australian Faunal Directory.

items.title: Epyaxa subidaria
items.content_text: The dark spots on the upper area of the wings is from the metal sheet it landed on.

items.title: Chloroclystis approximata
items.content_text: This is a very worn specimen with a lot of scale loss, hence the light colour and indistinct lines.

items.content_text: Second image shows ventral (underside) view.

items.title: Praxis pandesma
items.content_text: Antennae orangish which is an identification feature of this species. Second photo shows close-up.

items.title: Chlorocoma sp. (5)
items.content_text: The pink tips on the fringe differ from C. assimilis and no lines differ from C. dichloraria.

items.title: Trichiocercus spp.
items.content_text: I cannot see the black body to make it sp. (1) but it appears to be at least grey which suggests that it is not T. sparshalli.

items.title: Discophlebia catocalina
items.content_text: Larvae feed on Eucalypt leaves.

items.title: Anestia semiochrea
items.content_text: The female is flightless.

items.title: Eccymatoge callizona
items.content_text: There are three forms of this species - intermediate form (as shown and appears to be less common), plain form and white-patched form.

items.title: Cirphis ebriosa
items.content_text: Second image shows some of the underside of wings. Dark markings can be variable.

items.title: Discophlebia celaena
items.content_text: Second image shows close-up of head.

items.title: Hypobapta diffundens
items.content_text: Second image shows close-up of eggs.

items.title: Gastrinodes argoplaca
items.content_text: This species is in the group referred to as 'bark moth' because of the lines, colour and resting pose.  When sitting on tree/shrub bark, it is camouflaged to protect it from predation.

items.title: Melanodes anthracitaria
items.content_text: Beautiful brown markings shows variability.

items.title: Melanodes anthracitaria
items.content_text: This species is variable.  It can be dark grey or lighter grey with black lines.  It can also have light brown markings on both forewing and hindwing (see next observation). Largish moth; eight appeared at the light-trap.

items.title: Pararguda rufescens
items.content_text: Flits around when first arriving but once settled, usually patient with the photographer.

items.title: Nisista serrata
items.content_text: Second image shows the antennae.

items.title: Chrysodeixis argentifera
items.content_text: The S shaped white spot on the forewing is an ID feature of this species. Some scales have been worn off but interesting that the tufts are in good shape still.

items.title: Chloroclystis filata
items.content_text: Resting pose displays the hindwing shape which is an ID feature of this species.

items.title: Capusa senilis
items.content_text: Underside of wings helpful in identification. Second image shows the black spot on the hindwing underside is a feature of this species.

items.title: Anemosa exanthes
items.content_text: Second image displays the bright yellow hind-wing.  The resting position of this species is the 'tent' position but when flying the hindwing colour is more obvious. Five came to the light despite the cold night air.

items.title: Cycloprorodes melanoxysta
items.content_text: This species comes to the light readily however only once in the past has it landed on the sheet.  Invariably it sits on the ground using the stones and leave litter as camouflage.  This image was not posed but rather an opportunistic observation which portrays the similarity of the leaf to the moth wing shape, colour and markings.

items.title: Uresiphita ornithopteralis
items.content_text: The hindwing is the feature of this rather dull, brown moth.

items.title: Oxycanus rufescens
items.content_text: Second image shows hindwings.

items.title: Smyriodes trigramma
items.content_text: Second image shows head and antennae.  The resting pose is unusual.

items.content_text: Second image shows head and antennae

items.title: Proteuxoa cinereicollis
items.content_text: Second image shows close-up of head

items.content_text: Additional two images show hindwing colour and view of resting position from the top.

items.title: Hylaeora caustopis
items.content_text: Second image shows head and face

items.content_text: Second image shows wings spread.

items.title: Abantiades marcidus
items.content_text: Second image is of head and antennae.

items.title: Monoctenia smerintharia
items.content_text: Lots of these flying tonight, had about 15 of them at the light-trap.

items.title: Hylaeora eucalypti
items.content_text: Second image is of head and scales that form the tuft

items.title: Chrysolarentia gypsomela
items.content_text: Second image shows head and antennae.

items.title: Monoctenia falernaria
items.content_text: Additional image of the head (note the beautiful pink forehead and chest)

items.title: Mnesampela heliochrysa
items.content_text: Two additional images - one from the side and also one of the head.

items.title: Spilosoma glatignyi
items.content_text: Quite a few attracted to the light-trap despite the full moon.

items.title: Spilosoma glatignyi
items.content_text: Very dark form.

items.title: Proteuxoa bistrigula
items.content_text: Thanks to Marilyn Hewish for ID.

items.title: Mnesampela lenaea
items.content_text: Landed on the window - attracted by the outdoor house light.

items.title: Anthela denticulata
items.content_text: This species has a very short adult flight period which appears to be synchronised across a wide area.

items.title: Chrysolarentia vicissata
items.content_text: Additional photo shows underside of the wings.

items.title: Asthenoptycha spp.
items.content_text: Such an under-studied group of moths, it may be a while before this can be identified to species level.

items.title: Chrysodeixis eriosoma
items.content_text: The absence of a tiny silver 's' on each forewing distinguishes it from a related species - Chrysodeixis argentifera.  Additional image shows wings spread.

items.title: Doratifera oxleyi
items.content_text: Males are about a third of the size of the female.  Only one male and about 20 females to the light-trap this evening.

items.title: Oenosandra boisduvalii
items.content_text: Additional image shows head and face.

items.title: Nepticulidae spp.
items.content_text: This moth is about 2mm in length and from the group known as pigmy moths.  A characteristic, besides their tiny size, are the eye-caps.  They are extremely difficult to photograph even with a good macro lens.

items.title: Edosa spp.
items.content_text: The reddish line within the brown forewing end-tips is a definite marking rather than caused by the camera angle or flash.  Both forewings are marked alike.

items.title: Noctuidae spp.
items.content_text: At present, Australian Faunal Directory has this moth listed in the category of Species Inquirenda.  However, it has been described as Mamestra dictyota by Lower in 1902.  It is in the subfamily of Noctuinae, Tribe Hadenini.

items.title: Pararguda nasuta
items.content_text: Second image included showing wing shape.

items.title: Proteuxoa paratorna
items.content_text: This moth is variable but the black mark on the side of the palpi is an ID feature.

items.title: Proteuxoa hydraecioides
items.content_text: Side view included in second image.

items.title: Acrocercops spp.
items.content_text: So little work has been done on these tiny moths - unable to put a species name to this.

items.title: Dialectica scalariella
items.content_text: This tiny moth is about 3-4mm long.

items.title: Dichelopa spp.
items.content_text: Very similar to Dichelopa tarsodes and might be that species however the three pinned specimens held at ANIC are noted from larvae collected at Mt Gladstone near Cooma, New South Wales.

items.title: Salma pyrastis
items.content_text: Showing off the beautiful, bright orange hindwing.

items.title: Niceteria macrocosma
items.content_text: I have photographed this two different years in Lerderderg State Park but this is the first for me in the Brisbane Ranges.

items.title: Entometa spp.
items.content_text: This very gravid female came to the light-trap.  She began laying eggs shortly after arriving and deposited them in 3 areas.  I am unable to determine the exact species.  A series of images are presented including the eggs as they are being deposited on the ground.

items.title: Acrocercops irrorata
items.content_text: This moth is about 4 - 5mm in length from head to end of wings

items.title: Endoxyla lichenea
items.content_text: Thanks to Axel Kallies for ID.

items.title: Eochrois epidesma
items.content_text: A bit battered around its head area.

items.title: Maroga melanostigma
items.content_text: Last time I photographed this was in 2012.

items.title: Endoxyla encalypti
items.content_text: This is an unusual resting position for E. encalypti.  There were so many bugs on the sheet that I think this elevated position is a defensive pose.  At least it gave me a chance to get a good image of its head including palps.  See second image.

items.title: Dithalama cosmospila
items.content_text: Perfect condition - even the wing fringes are not marred.

items.title: Lomera boisduvalii
items.content_text: These usually have major scale loss - getting one in this condition suggests that it has recently emerged.  Females are flightless.

items.title: Chrysodeixis argentifera
items.content_text: Two images - second shows side view.

items.title: Proteuxoa sanguinipuncta
items.content_text: Shadow at the head is created because of the angle of the flash - uncooperative moth.

items.title: Scopula optivata
items.content_text: Sometimes things are not perfect when a moth emerges from the cocoon.  It seemed to be able to fly without difficulty.

items.title: Musotima ochropteralis
items.content_text: Difficult to get a clear image due to the almost constant flutter of the wings.

items.title: Earias paralella
items.content_text: Although the scales are worn, there is still evidence of the green stripes on the forewings.

items.title: Ardozyga stratifera
items.content_text: This is in the Subfamily Ardozyga (Protolechia) Group.

items.title: Enchocrates picrophylla
items.content_text: Two images

items.title: Mythimna convecta
items.content_text: Two images - one of the head/palps.

items.title: Anthela varia
items.content_text: Two images

items.title: Epicoma contristis
items.content_text: Hanging on to the leg of a large Praying Mantis may not be the best decision this moth has ever made.

items.title: Leistarcha scitissimella
items.content_text: Two images, different aspects.

items.title: Sympycnodes dunnorum
items.content_text: Had four come to the light-trap and three had worn scales, one to the point of almost none left on the forewings.  They flutter around and do not come to rest very easily.  Once they have landed, they look for something to get beneath.

items.title: Leptozestis sp.
items.content_text: Two photos

items.title: Epithetica typhoscia
items.content_text: Very small moth - 5 to 7mm from head to wingtip.

items.content_text: Two photos.

items.content_text: Two photos.

items.title: Casbia celidosema
items.content_text: A little worn.

items.title: Agrotis porphyricollis
items.content_text: Light colour form with second image showing head close up.

items.title: Chlorocoma cadmaria
items.content_text: I think this is probably newly emerged - not a mark on the scales nor loss of fringe on the wings.

items.title: Glyphipterix chrysoplanetis
items.content_text: These moths often have a metallic appearance.  The 'palps' area has an interesting ID feature as displayed in this image.

items.title: Epithetica typhoscia
items.content_text: Finally found an ID for this species.  Had listed it as undescribed.

items.title: Cecidomyiinae spp., Epidesmia hypenaria
items.content_text: I have no idea of the identification of the 'free-loader'.

items.title: Agrotis porphyricollis
items.content_text: Dark colour form.

items.title: Spilosoma curvata
items.content_text: Shows the variability, especially the colour, but also the lines/markings on the wings.

items.title: Wingia lambertella
items.content_text: Side view in second image.

items.title: Neola semiaurata
items.content_text: Image of head close up in second image.

items.title: Praxis sp.
items.content_text: This genus will be featured in MOV8 which is due to be published in 2017.

items.title: Parosteodes fictiliaria
items.content_text: This species can be variable.

items.title: Leptocroca sanguinolenta
items.content_text: Had 10 of these on the sheet - must have been a large emergence event.

items.title: Fisera sp. (5)
items.content_text: Listed in Moths of Victoria Part 5.

items.title: Oxycanus silvanus
items.content_text: Still seeing a couple of these each evening.

items.title: Chelepteryx chalepteryx
items.content_text: Had 6 females on the sheet this evening.

items.title: Oxycanus silvanus
items.content_text: According to Moths of Victoria Part 6, this moth is easily recognised by the long rami on the antennae and the long labial palps.  It occurs in the dry sclerophyll forest and woodlands.  Spots on the wings may vary from obvious to obsolete.

items.title: Androchela milvaria
items.content_text: Androchela milvaria is very variable.  It has a large cloudy spot on each forewing - this spot is not always obvious if it is the colour form shown in this photo.  Its peak flight time is April.

items.title: Pterolocera spp.
items.content_text: This is in the 'Lined Group' known as the Grass Anthelids.  It has remarkable antennae and the female is flightless.

items.title: Stibaroma melanotoxa
items.content_text: Some individuals have pale patches on thorax and forewings.  (MOV Part 5)

items.title: Opsirhina lechriodes
items.content_text: The white spot on the forewing is less pronounced in the female.

items.title: Scioglyptis lyciaria
items.content_text: White patch on forewings is ID feature.

items.title: Hestiochora spp.
items.content_text: Unable to determine exact species ID but the Genus has been confirmed by Axel Kallies.

items.title: Acanthodela protophaes
items.content_text: This moth is practising its Wild-Wild-West skills (like riding a horse except this ride might just eat it on the way!)

items.title: Eudesmeola lawsoni
items.content_text: Mass emergence this night - had about a dozen on the sheet all at once (both male and female).

items.title: Prepalla tephrina
items.content_text: 2nd image shows palps up close.

items.title: Abantiades labyrinthicus
items.content_text: Autumn moths are just getting started - helps with a little rain shower.

items.title: Bedellia somnulentella
items.content_text: This moth is really small, about 2mm in length.

items.title: Acrocercops ophiodes
items.content_text: 2mm long X 1mm or less wide.  A real challenge to photograph.

items.title: Corgatha molybdophaes
items.content_text: This small moth's scales are a bit worn but still beautiful.

items.title: Casbia melanops
items.content_text: First new one for 2017

items.title: Clania ignobilis
items.content_text: Wing scales easily come off making the wings appear clear.  The female is flightless.

items.title: Thudaca mimodora
items.content_text: Chased this one all around the swamp.

items.title: Artigisa melanephele
items.content_text: Last time I photographed this species in the same location was in  2012.

items.title: Cleora sp. (2)
items.content_text: The ID is from Moths of Victoria - Part 7

items.title: Opodiphthera helena
items.content_text: The female is larger than the male.

items.title: Sandava scitisignata
items.content_text: Fresh and newly emerged.

items.title: Chloroclystis testulata
items.content_text: Unusual colour form

items.title: Hippotion scrofa
items.content_text: This moth bounced around and then landed upside down.  It remained that way long enough for me to get a photo, then righted itself and flew away.

items.title: Neola semiaurata
items.content_text: This moth has a resting position with wings tucked tight to the body.  Two further photos show features - no doubt this specimen was newly emerged because there was no damage to the scales.

items.title: (Cymatophora) aspera
items.content_text: This is the beginning of the flight time for this moth - usually comes to the light in the earlier hours of evening.

items.title: (Cymatophora) aspera
items.content_text: Called the 'Varied Geometrid' for a reason.

items.title: Scopula rubraria
items.content_text: A ride on the wild side.

items.title: Spilosoma glatignyi
items.content_text: The GPS record from the camera is not quite right - it should be -37.806631/144.296932

items.title: Abantiades marcidus
items.content_text: Common name is Red Gum Ghost Moth.

items.title: Spilosoma glatignyi
items.content_text: Came in head first, provided an underside view and eventually settled in a better position.

items.title: Circopetes obtusata
items.content_text: Both male and female came to the lit sheet - not much significant difference in size but the body structure and antennae assist in the gender determination.

items.title: Endoxyla encalypti
items.content_text: Note the bright blue on the top of the head - very useful when determining this species.

items.title: Achyra affinitalis
items.content_text: Mating pair.

items.title: Praxis porphyretica
items.content_text: Both top view and underside from same pose.

items.title: (Cymatophora) aspera
items.content_text: Note the fuzz underside.

items.title: (Boarmia) panconita
items.content_text: White spots on antennae an identification feature.

items.title: Amphiclasta lygaea
items.content_text: Camera geotag is incorrect - the correct GPS location is -37.806641/144.296921

items.title: Ciampa arietaria
items.content_text: These images include both female and male of the species.  The male is about 1/3 the size of the female and duller in colour.

items.title: Monoctenia smerintharia
items.content_text: Had three come to the lit sheet on one night.  Last photo shows a typical tent-shape resting pose once settled.

items.title: Furcatrox spp.
items.content_text: Furcatrox species have yet to be sorted out due to the need for genitalia inspection and confirmation through that process.

items.title: Pataeta conspicienda
items.content_text: This species name is a synonym of Pataeta carbo.

items.title: Pararguda rufescens
items.content_text: According to P. Marriott, the extra bit (tuft) on the moth's back is probably eggs and scales.  It may or may not be from this species but this male moth has acquired it somehow.

items.title: Circopetes obtusata
items.content_text: Images provide view from top and underneath wings.

items.title: Araeopaschia spp.
items.content_text: This is an undescribed species.

items.title: Dichromodes obtusata
items.content_text: This moth is in the Dichromodes obtusata complex which needs more work of the various populations.  This complex is variable.

items.title: Philobota productella
items.content_text: Many males and one female appeared on the sheet.  The female mated with more than one male during the session.

items.title: Casbia farinalis
items.content_text: This group is being revised and at present I do not know of a species name for the moth.

items.title: Poecilasthena spp.
items.content_text: This small moth does not have a species name as yet but is very similar in appearance to Poecilasthena scoliota found in Western Australia.

items.title: Rhuma sp. (3)
items.content_text: Female and male of same species at the moth sheet.

items.title: Aphantes melanochorda
items.content_text: This moth has been around a bit and the silver colour is caused by loss of scales on the surface of the wings.

items.title: Genduara acedesta
items.content_text: This is the female of the species.

items.title: Endoxyla encalypti
items.content_text: This front view shows the distinguishing blue on top of the head.  When they are newly emerged, this can be quite florescent.

items.title: Entometa guttularis
items.content_text: This is a female

items.title: Paralaea porphyrinaria
items.content_text: This is a male in the relaxed position.

items.title: Endoxyla spp.
items.content_text: These can be difficult to identify correctly - the probable ID is either Endoxyla edwardsorum or Endoxyla grisea.

items.title: Chrysonoma spp.
items.content_text: This is very similar to a species noted as Chrysonoma sp near tentatella.

items.title: Eublemma inconspicua
items.content_text: This was incorrectly identified as Eublemma rivula.  Moths of Victoria 8 has assisted in the correct species identification.

items.title: Didymoctenia exsuperata
items.content_text: Top image is the female of the species.  The lower image is the male of the species and smaller in size.

items.title: Anestia ombrophanes
items.content_text: This is a lighter colour form - can be variable.

items.title: Metrocampa biplaga
items.content_text: This moth has been reclassified to (Azelina) biplaga

items.title: Arhodia lasiocamparia
items.content_text: Top photo is the female, lower photo is the male.

items.title: Opsirhina lechriodes
items.content_text: Both are same species: one injured with no wing spot on left side and no 'snout'.

items.title: Sinpunctiptilia emissalis
items.content_text: Also known as Platyptilia emissalis. Feeds on Digger's Speedwell (Derwentia perfoliata).

items.title: Alucita phricodes
items.content_text: Unmistakable - has both fore and hindwings wings deeply cleft into numerous narrow lobes.  This one was about 1.8cm from wing tip to wing tip.

items.title: Phrataria transcissata
items.content_text: This moth is particularly difficult to photograph because it rarely sits with its wings open.

items.title: Palleopa innotata
items.content_text: Male and female of the species
